Investment Banking | Revolving Door 
Dag Skattum Is Set to Return to JPMorgan as a Vice Chairman


				By Chad Bray			
November 17, 2014 6:38 am
November 17, 2014 6:38 am







PhotoJPMorgan Chase offices in London.Credit Simon Newman/Reuters
LONDON — Dag Skattum, the former co-head of global mergers and acquisitions at JPMorgan Chase, is expected to rejoin the bank in January as vice chairman for Europe, the Middle East and Africa.
According to an internal memorandum seen by DealBook, Mr. Skattum will be based in London and will report to Carlos Hernandez and Jeff Urwin, JPMorgan’s co-heads of global banking.
Mr. Skattum will act as chairman of a new global investment banking strategic advisory council within JPMorgan. He also will work closely with Sjoerd Leenart, JPMorgan’s head of its operations in the Middle East and North Africa, to coordinate client strategy in sub-Saharan Africa.
“Dag’s expertise will be critical in helping us continue the evolution of the firm’s growing business in the region,” Daniel E. Pinto, the chief executive of JPMorgan’s corporate and investment bank, said in the memo.
A JPMorgan spokeswoman confirmed Monday that Mr. Skattum would be rejoining the bank next year.
Mr. Skattum joined JPMorgan in 1986 and worked for the bank for 21 years in a variety of roles in New York and in London, including as co-head of global mergers and acquisitions.
He left the bank in 2007 to join the private equity firm TPG Capital. He most recently headed the London office of One Thousand & One Voices, a social investment fund focused on sub-Saharan Africa.




